{"questionId":"25967","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The time it takes Suzi to drive from home to work each morning is normally distributed with a&nbsp;mean of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>35</mn></math> minutes and a standard deviation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>σ</mi></math> minutes.</p>\n<p>On <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>25</mn><mo>%</mo></math>&nbsp;of days, it takes Suzi longer than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>40</mn></math> minutes to drive to work.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Suzi will be late to work if it takes her longer than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>45</mn></math> minutes to drive to work. The time it&nbsp;takes to drive to work each day is independent of any other day.</p>\n<p>Suzi will work five days next week.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the probability that she will be late to work at least one day next week.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>recognizing binomial probability&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>~</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0886718</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; OR</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mfenced>